# Research Protocol

## The Invariant

**Agents raise the flag. Users do the research. Agents record and propose. Users approve.**

This invariant is absolute. No step in this protocol may be reordered or skipped. An agent that conducts its own research, synthesizes a recommendation from existing docs alone, or proceeds past a Spike without explicit user approval is in violation.

---

## A. Core Component Detection — When a Spike Is REQUIRED

A Spike must be created, and implementation must stop, before any Story is implemented that touches one of the following 17 core components. The canonical list lives in `docs/architecture/component-map.md`.

| Component | ID | What counts as "touching" it |
|---|---|---|
| Trust & Consent Service | C1 | Any change to auth identity, consent scopes, share grants, revocation logic, or the cross-patient opt-in gate |
| Raw Context Vault | C2 | Any change to immutability rules, append-only guarantees, provenance metadata schema, or retention logic |
| Ingestion Layer | C3 | Any new source-type adapter that deviates from the existing adapter pattern, or any change to how adapters write into the Vault |
| Processing Pipeline | C4 | Any change to processing order, entity extraction logic, classification rules, quality/confidence scoring, or entity resolution |
| Evidence & Provenance Service | C5 | Any change to how evidence is scored, weighted, traced, or linked; any change to the "no orphan claims" enforcement |
| Knowledge Graph Store | C6 | Any change to node or edge types, scoring algorithms, auto-linking logic, or causal edge semantics (e.g. `may_explain`) |
| Health Thread Engine + State Machine | C7 | Any change to lifecycle transitions, status rules, linking logic, or the definition of an "unresolved concern" |
| Six Memories Store | C8 | Any change to what each memory type stores, how it is structured, or its access patterns |
| Continuity & Closure Engine | C9 | Any change to the pending item ledger logic, referral lifecycle rules, result tracker semantics, or closure conditions |
| Safety & Governance Gate | C10 | Any change to any evaluation layer — rules engine, LLM gate, output routing, do-not-diagnose enforcement, bias controls |
| Correction Service | C11 | Any change to how user corrections are captured, layered, or linked to source-linked layers |
| Notification & Audit Service | C12 | Any change to the append-only audit trail schema, event semantics, or notification trigger logic |
| API & Contract Layer | C13 | Any schema change or versioning decision that affects multiple components or external consumers |
| Investigation Engine | C14 | Any change to the Investigation object, its lifecycle/status, scope flags, participant model, or the Investigate loop-step semantics |
| Theory Service | C15 | Any change to the Theory object, its status/safety levels, evidence-for/against linking, or theory-type classification |
| External Evidence Graph + Research Watch | C16 | Any change to the separate external-evidence store, source-quality tiers, relevance-link semantics, or curated retrieval/watch |
| Workspace, Role & Grant Layer | C17 | Any change to the role/grant model, workspace scoping, grant fields (purpose/duration/comment/export/invite), or institution/researcher access governance |

### Not required — agent may implement directly

A Spike is NOT required for:
- UI components that only render existing data (no new safety gate logic, no schema changes)
- Infrastructure or deployment changes (hosting, CI, environment config)
- Feature-layer work that consumes core services through existing stable contracts without modifying core logic
- Bug fixes in non-core areas
- Documentation updates
- Adding a new data source that uses an existing ingestion adapter pattern without deviation
- Purely cosmetic or copy changes

**When in doubt, treat it as a core component touch.** Creating a Spike that turns out to be unnecessary has no cost. Proceeding without a Spike on a core component decision may introduce irrecoverable architectural debt.

---

## B. The "Raise Hand" Behavior — Exact Format

When a Spike is required, the agent must **stop implementation immediately** and output EXACTLY this structure before taking any other action. No partial implementation, no exploratory code, no placeholder logic.

```
⚑ RESEARCH REQUIRED

Story: <WEL-XXX — Story title>
Core component touched: <component name and ID, e.g. "Health Thread Engine + State Machine (C7)">
Question that must be answered before implementation:
  <Specific, precise question — not vague. Not "how does X work" but a crisp decision question,
   e.g. "How does the Pattern Detection engine determine temporal precedence between two co-occurring
   events? Specifically: do we use timestamp order, user-reported order, or a confidence-weighted
   combination?">

I will now:
1. Create a Jira Spike that blocks WEL-XXX
2. Create a Decision Record stub at docs/decisions/<slug>.md

I cannot proceed with implementation until you provide research results.
```

The agent must **not** propose its own answer to the question. The question is left open. The agent may read existing docs in `docs/` and `archive/` to formulate the question precisely — but reading existing docs does not constitute research and does not resolve the Spike.

The slug for the Decision Record is derived from the question: kebab-case, max 6 words, no article words. Example: `health-thread-temporal-precedence`.

---

## C. What Agents CANNOT Do During Research

While a Spike is open against a Story:

- Agents may NOT conduct external research (web search, reading papers, fetching external URLs) on behalf of this Spike
- Agents may NOT synthesize a recommendation from existing docs alone and label it "research" or "proposed decision"
- Agents may NOT implement any part of the blocked Story — not even scaffolding, interfaces, or placeholder logic
- Agents may NOT open a related Story that has the same unresolved question and implement that instead
- Agents MAY read existing docs in `docs/` and `archive/` to formulate the question precisely, but this does not replace research and does not resolve the Spike
- Agents MAY work on unrelated Stories that do not touch the same open question

---

## D. When Research Results Are Provided

When the user provides research results (in any form — text, links, uploaded documents, verbal summary, paste of external content), the agent must:

1. **Record** the results verbatim or as a faithful summary in the Decision Record under "Research provided" — do not paraphrase in a way that changes meaning. Record the date received.
2. **Write** "Approaches considered" based ONLY on the provided research — not the agent's own knowledge or training data. Each approach must be traceable to something the user provided.
3. **Write** a proposed "Decision" — one clear, concrete statement. The agent proposes; the user approves.
4. **Present** the completed Decision Record and wait. Format exactly:

```
DECISION RECORD READY FOR APPROVAL

File: docs/decisions/<slug>.md
Decision: <one-sentence summary of the proposed decision>

[Review file]  [Approve]  [Edit]  [Reject]
```

The agent does not close the Spike, unblock the Story, or proceed to implementation until the user provides explicit approval.

---

## E. On Approval

When the user explicitly approves the Decision Record:

1. Update the Decision Record: set `Status` to `Approved`, fill `Date approved` with today's date
2. Update the Jira Spike: add a comment linking to `docs/decisions/<slug>.md`, then transition to Done
3. Confirm the `blocks` link from the Spike to the Story is resolved (remove or mark resolved as Jira allows)
4. Set `re-eval:clean` on the Story (removing any `re-eval:blocked-by-change` label)
5. Commit the approved Decision Record with message: `"Approve decision: <slug>"`
6. The Story is now unblocked — implementation may proceed

If the user rejects or edits the proposed decision: update the record, re-present under "DECISION RECORD READY FOR APPROVAL", and wait again. Do not proceed until a clear approval is received.

---

## F. Spike Metadata Rules

When creating the Jira Spike:

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| `issue_type` | `Story` (Jira Cloud next-gen uses Story for Spikes — verify available types if the project config has changed) |
| Summary | `[Spike] <question in one sentence — specific, not vague>` |
| Labels | `layer:<x>`, `component:<x>`, `impact:<x>`, `re-eval:clean`, `triage-YYYY-MM-DD-NNN` (current session) |
| Priority | One tier below the blocked Story's priority. High Story → Medium Spike. Medium Story → Low Spike. A Spike is never P0. See `jira-prioritization-logic.mdc`. |
| Fix Version | Same phase as the blocked Story |
| Description | Must include: (1) the specific question, (2) why it matters — what breaks if we guess wrong, (3) what will be unblocked when resolved, (4) the line: "Research results must be provided by the user. Agents may not self-research." |
| Issue link | `blocks` → the relevant Story key |

The `triage-YYYY-MM-DD-NNN` label must be consistent with the current triage session. If this Spike is created outside a triage run, start a new session label for the current date.

---

## G. Decision Record File Rules

Every Decision Record lives at `docs/decisions/<slug>.md`. The template is at `docs/decisions/_template.md`.

- Slugs are kebab-case, max 6 words, derived from the question (not the component name)
- Records are append-only once approved — never edit an approved record in place
- To supersede an approved record: create a new record and link to the old one in the new record's "Context" section
- Records are NOT bible files — they do not require governance approval to read or reference
- Records do require the full approval flow before being set to `Approved` status

---

## H. Agent Behavior Summary

| Situation | Agent action |
|---|---|
| Story touches a core component (C1–C13) | Stop. Output "⚑ RESEARCH REQUIRED" block. Create Jira Spike. Create Decision Record stub. Wait. |
| Spike is open against a Story | Do not implement. Do not self-research. May work on unrelated Stories. |
| User provides research results | Record faithfully → write Approaches + proposed Decision → present "DECISION RECORD READY FOR APPROVAL" → wait. |
| User approves decision | Update record status → close Spike → unblock Story → commit record → begin implementation. |
| User rejects or edits decision | Update record → re-present → wait for approval. |
| User says "skip research" explicitly | Record the override in the Spike description and in the Decision Record stub under "Context". Close the Spike. Proceed to implementation. Add `[research-skipped]` to the commit message. |
| Ambiguous whether a component is touched | Treat as a core component touch. Raise hand. Better to create an unnecessary Spike than to miss one. |
| Multiple Stories touch the same open question | One Spike covers all. Add additional `blocks` links from the Spike to each Story. Do not create duplicate Spikes for the same question. |

